"# Chapter 7: Voices

**Chapter question:** What makes a cello sound like a cello, and not like a flute?

Up until now, every note we've played—whether a single pitch from Chapter 1's `(tone 440 1)` or the entire harmonized *Twinkle Twinkle* from Chapter 6—has lived inside the same plain sonic wrapper. We've changed *pitch*, *duration*, *velocity*, and even stacked notes into chords, but the **quality** of the sound itself—the thing that makes a violin a violin and a trumpet a trumpet—has been mostly opaque to us. We've asked *what* to play and *when*, but not *with what voice*.

This chapter changes that. We will learn how **timbre**—the texture or color of a sound—emerges from the **harmonic content** of a waveform, and we will use the Web Audio API's `createPeriodicWave` to **design our own voices** by specifying exactly which harmonics ring and how loud. By the end, you will be able to tune a voice that sounds like a cello section, a clarinet choir, or something entirely new—and play it just as easily as you've been playing the default piano.

**We call it \"music,\" but we are really dealing with sound.** A \"voice\" is not a metaphor—it is a specific recipe of sine waves, mixed at precise amplitudes, that your ear hears as a unified tone. This chapter makes that recipe explicit and puts it under your control.

---

## 1. What is timbre?

Play these two programs and listen:

```scheme
;; A bare 220 Hz sine wave
(tone 220 1)
```

```scheme
;; A 220 Hz tone with the default \"piano\" voice
(note/strike 'A3 'quarter 0.8)
```

Both are the same pitch (A3 = 220 Hz), but they sound completely different. The first is **pure**—smooth, glassy, a single sine wave with no texture. The second is **rich**—warm, percussive, full of detail. That difference is **timbre**.

**Timbre** is the quality that lets you tell a violin from a trumpet even when they play the same note at the same loudness. It is what makes a voice sound \"bright\" or \"dark,\" \"hollow\" or \"reedy.\" And it is **not magic**—it is the result of **which harmonics are present and how loud they are**.

A **harmonic** is a frequency that is an integer multiple of a **fundamental** frequency. If the fundamental is 220 Hz (A3), the harmonics are:

- 1× = 220 Hz (the fundamental itself)
- 2× = 440 Hz (the first harmonic, one octave up)
- 3× = 660 Hz
- 4× = 880 Hz
- 5× = 1100 Hz
- … and so on

A sine wave, like `(tone 220 1)`, contains **only the fundamental**—no harmonics at all. That is why it sounds so pure and featureless. Every other instrument—every real-world sound—is a **mixture** of the fundamental plus some subset of its harmonics, each ringing at its own amplitude. The **harmonic profile**—which harmonics are loud, which are quiet, which are missing—is what gives an instrument its voice.

[VISUAL: Spectrum diagram showing a sine wave (single spike at 220 Hz) versus a rich tone (fundamental + harmonics at 440, 660, 880, 1100, 1320 Hz, decreasing in amplitude). Horizontal axis = frequency (Hz), vertical axis = amplitude. Two panels side-by-side.]

<!-- BUILD: render spectrum diagrams showing sine (one spike) vs. rich harmonic tone (fundamental + 6–8 harmonics, amplitudes falling roughly exponentially). Use dot-matrix line rendering on Curator-16 substrate. -->

---

## 2. Building a voice from harmonics

The Web Audio API gives us a tool called `createPeriodicWave` that lets us specify **exactly which harmonics to include and how loud they should be**. Instead of accepting a pre-built waveform (sine, square, sawtooth), `createPeriodicWave` takes two arrays:

- **Real** (the cosine coefficients)
- **Imaginary** (the sine coefficients)

These arrays encode the **Fourier series** that describes the waveform. For our purposes, the **real** array is where we place the amplitudes of each harmonic (starting with the fundamental), and the **imaginary** array is usually all zeros (which means no phase shift—every harmonic starts at the same moment).

Concretely: if you want a tone with a strong fundamental, a weaker second harmonic, and a very quiet third harmonic, you would write:

```scheme
(define cello-profile
  '(0.0    ; DC offset (always 0)
    1.0    ; fundamental (full strength)
    0.4    ; 2nd harmonic (weaker)
    0.1))  ; 3rd harmonic (quiet)
```

The **first number is always 0.0**—it represents the DC offset, which we never use in audio. The **second number** is the fundamental, the **third** is the first harmonic (2×), the **fourth** is the second harmonic (3×), and so on.

Here is a complete program that **creates a custom voice** using that profile and plays a single note with it *[needs: GAP-6]*:

```scheme
(define cello-profile
  '(0.0 1.0 0.4 0.1))

(define (make-voice profile)
  ;; [needs: GAP-6] — createPeriodicWave support
  ;; This will call:
  ;;   audioContext.createPeriodicWave(
  ;;     Float32Array(profile),
  ;;     Float32Array(zeros-of-same-length)
  ;;   )
  ;; and return a voice handle
  (create-periodic-wave profile (make-list (length profile) 0.0)))

(define my-cello (make-voice cello-profile))

(note/strike 'C4 'half 0.8 my-cello)
```

<!-- BUILD: wire (create-periodic-wave real-list imag-list) → call audioContext.createPeriodicWave, return a voice handle; wire (note/strike pitch dur velocity voice) to accept an optional voice argument and use it instead of the default oscillator waveform. GAP-6. -->

*[needs: GAP-6]* — The `create-periodic-wave` and voice-selection machinery are not yet wired, but the **shape** is here: you define a harmonic profile as a list, you call `make-voice` to turn it into a playable voice, and then you pass that voice to `note/strike` (or any other note-placement verb) as an optional argument. Once GAP-6 closes, this code will run exactly as written.

---

## 3. Designing a section voice

Real orchestras do not use single instruments—they use **sections**: eight cellos, twelve violins, four horns. A section has a **thicker, more blended sound** than a solo instrument, because the slight tuning and timing variations between players **blur the attack** and **widen the harmonic envelope**.

We can model a section by **choosing a harmonic profile that emphasizes the lower harmonics and tapers off quickly**. Here is a **warm string-section voice**:

```scheme
(define warm-strings-profile
  '(0.0    ; DC
    1.0    ; fundamental
    0.6    ; 2nd
    0.3    ; 3rd
    0.15   ; 4th
    0.08   ; 5th
    0.04   ; 6th
    0.02)) ; 7th

(define warm-strings (make-voice warm-strings-profile))
```

The fundamental is full-strength, the second harmonic is moderately strong, and each successive harmonic is roughly **half as loud** as the one before. This gives a **smooth, full, non-piercing** tone—exactly what you hear from a violin or cello section playing *legato*.

Now play a chord with it *[needs: GAP-6]*:

```scheme
(define warm-strings-profile
  '(0.0 1.0 0.6 0.3 0.15 0.08 0.04 0.02))

(define (make-voice profile)
  (create-periodic-wave profile (make-list (length profile) 0.0)))

(define warm-strings (make-voice warm-strings-profile))

(define (play-chord pitches dur velocity voice)
  (for-each (lambda (p)
              (note/strike p dur velocity voice))
            pitches))

(play-chord '(C4 E4 G4) 'whole 0.7 warm-strings)
```

<!-- BUILD: ensure (note/strike pitch dur velocity voice) schedules the note with the given PeriodicWave voice; the chord plays three simultaneous notes, all using the warm-strings voice. GAP-6. -->

You should hear a **rich, unified chord**—not three separate sine tones, but a **blended section sound**.

[VISUAL: Staff rendering of a C major triad (C4, E4, G4) held for a whole note, with three note-sprites (whole notes) stacked vertically on the treble clef. The note-sprites are bopping slowly (whole-note tempo = languid). Caption: \"A section-voiced chord—warm strings.\"]

