## 4. Bright versus dark

The **brightness** of a voice is determined by how much high-harmonic energy it has. A **bright** voice emphasizes the upper harmonics; a **dark** voice suppresses them.

Here are two profiles—one bright, one dark:

```scheme
;; Bright (flute-like)
(define bright-profile
  '(0.0 0.7 0.5 0.4 0.3 0.25 0.2 0.15 0.1))

;; Dark (bassoon-like)
(define dark-profile
  '(0.0 1.0 0.3 0.1 0.05 0.02 0.01 0.005 0.0))
```

The **bright profile** keeps harmonics 2–8 at relatively high levels (0.5, 0.4, 0.3, …). The **dark profile** drops them aggressively after the third harmonic. Play the same melody with each voice and the difference is unmistakable *[needs: GAP-6]*:

```scheme
(define bright-profile
  '(0.0 0.7 0.5 0.4 0.3 0.25 0.2 0.15 0.1))

(define dark-profile
  '(0.0 1.0 0.3 0.1 0.05 0.02 0.01 0.005 0.0))

(define (make-voice profile)
  (create-periodic-wave profile (make-list (length profile) 0.0)))

(define bright-voice (make-voice bright-profile))
(define dark-voice (make-voice dark-profile))

(define melody '(C4 D4 E4 F4 G4 F4 E4 D4 C4))

(define (play-melody pitches dur velocity voice)
  (let loop ((ps pitches) (beat 0))
    (if (null? ps)
        'done
        (begin
          (note/place-at (car ps) beat dur velocity voice)
          (loop (cdr ps) (+ beat 1))))))

;; Play with the bright voice
(play-melody melody 'quarter 0.75 bright-voice)

;; Wait, then play with the dark voice
;; (In practice, you would schedule this at beat 10 or use a sequencer)
;; (play-melody melody 'quarter 0.75 dark-voice)
```

<!-- BUILD: wire (note/place-at pitch beat dur velocity voice) to schedule a note at the given beat with the given voice. GAP-6. Run the melody twice in succession (or side-by-side if the sequencer allows overlapping tracks). -->

The bright voice sounds **airy, piercing, flute-like**. The dark voice sounds **warm, mellow, woody**. Same melody, same rhythm, same pitches—**different harmonic profiles**.

[VISUAL: Two spectrum diagrams side-by-side. Left: bright profile (harmonics 1–9, amplitudes decaying slowly). Right: dark profile (harmonics 1–9, steep drop after harmonic 3). Both showing the same fundamental frequency (e.g., 262 Hz = C4).]

<!-- BUILD: render two spectrum diagrams (dot-matrix line rendering, Curator-16 substrate) showing the harmonic amplitudes of bright-profile vs. dark-profile. Horizontal axis = harmonic number (1–9), vertical axis = amplitude (0.0–1.0). -->

---

## 5. Tuning your own voice

You now have the tools to **design any voice you can imagine**. The process is:

1. **Decide how many harmonics to include** (typically 6–12 is enough; beyond that, the ear can barely distinguish them).
2. **Set the amplitude of each harmonic** (between 0.0 and 1.0).
3. **Wrap the profile in `make-voice`** to get a playable voice handle.
4. **Pass the voice to `note/strike` or `note/place-at`** as the last argument.

Here is a **hollow, clarinet-like voice** (clarinets emphasize odd harmonics and suppress even ones):

```scheme
(define clarinet-profile
  '(0.0    ; DC
    1.0    ; fundamental
    0.0    ; 2nd (suppressed)
    0.6    ; 3rd (strong)
    0.0    ; 4th (suppressed)
    0.4    ; 5th (moderate)
    0.0    ; 6th (suppressed)
    0.2    ; 7th (weak)
    0.0))  ; 8th (suppressed)

(define (make-voice profile)
  (create-periodic-wave profile (make-list (length profile) 0.0)))

(define clarinet (make-voice clarinet-profile))

(note/strike 'D4 'half 0.8 clarinet)
```

<!-- BUILD: wire voice support for note/strike. GAP-6. -->

The result is **reedy, nasal, hollow**—exactly the quality of a clarinet in its middle register.

[VISUAL: Spectrum diagram of clarinet-profile, showing spikes at harmonics 1, 3, 5, 7 (odd only), with even harmonics (2, 4, 6, 8) at zero.]

<!-- BUILD: render spectrum of clarinet-profile—vertical bars at harmonics 1, 3, 5, 7 (heights = 1.0, 0.6, 0.4, 0.2), flat zero at 2, 4, 6, 8. Dot-matrix line rendering. -->

---

## 6. A tunable section-voice

Let's pull it all together into a **reusable function** that builds a section voice from a **decay rate**—a single parameter that controls how quickly the harmonics fall off. A **slow decay** gives a bright, rich voice; a **fast decay** gives a dark, mellow voice.

```scheme
(define (section-voice num-harmonics decay-rate)
  ;; Build a profile where each harmonic's amplitude is:
  ;;   amplitude[n] = (expt decay-rate (- n 1))
  ;; (The first element is always 0.0 for DC offset.)
  (let ((profile (cons 0.0
                       (map (lambda (n)
                              (expt decay-rate (- n 1)))
                            (iota num-harmonics 1)))))
    (make-voice profile)))

(define (make-voice profile)
  (create-periodic-wave profile (make-list (length profile) 0.0)))

;; A rich, bright section (decay = 0.7)
(define bright-section (section-voice 10 0.7))

;; A warm, dark section (decay = 0.5)
(define warm-section (section-voice 10 0.5))

;; A very mellow section (decay = 0.3)
(define mellow-section (section-voice 10 0.3))

;; Play a phrase with each
(define phrase '(C4 E4 G4 E4 C4))

(define (play-phrase pitches dur velocity voice)
  (let loop ((ps pitches) (beat 0))
    (if (null? ps)
        'done
        (begin
          (note/place-at (car ps) beat dur velocity voice)
          (loop (cdr ps) (+ beat 1))))))

(play-phrase phrase 'quarter 0.8 bright-section)
;; (then play with warm-section and mellow-section)
```

<!-- BUILD: wire (iota n start) → (list start (+ start 1) … (+ start n-1)). Wire expt, cons, map. Wire note/place-at with voice argument. GAP-6. -->

*[needs: GAP-6]* — Once `create-periodic-wave` and voice-selection are wired, you can **tune a section voice in real time** by adjusting the `decay-rate` parameter. A decay of **0.7** gives a **violin section**, **0.5** gives **cellos**, **0.3** gives **basses**. You are now conducting the harmonic content directly.

[VISUAL: Three spectrum diagrams stacked vertically, each showing 10 harmonics. Top: decay = 0.7 (slow falloff, bright). Middle: decay = 0.5 (medium falloff, warm). Bottom: decay = 0.3 (steep falloff, dark). Each labeled with its decay rate.]

<!-- BUILD: render three spectrum diagrams (dot-matrix, Curator-16) showing harmonic amplitudes for decay-rate = 0.7, 0.5, 0.3. Horizontal axis = harmonic number (1–10), vertical axis = amplitude (0.0–1.0). Stack vertically with labels. -->

