## Notes and Additional Considerations from r1 draft

*The following material comes from an earlier or parallel revision draft (r1 draft). It is preserved here because content costs thought — nothing gets thrown away. Some passages restate the chapter's core ideas in a different voice; others introduce examples or angles not covered above. Read as supplemental exercises for the same discipline.*

### A voice with one harmonic

The simplest periodic wave is a sine — just the fundamental, no harmonics above it. We already know that sound from `(tone freq dur)`. Let's define it as a voice anyway, to see the pattern.

*[needs: GAP-4]*

```scheme
;; A pure sine voice — only the first harmonic, amplitude 1.0
(define sine-voice
  (create-periodic-wave
    (list 1.0)))  ;; harmonic 1 at full strength

(note/strike 60 'quarter 0.8 sine-voice)  ;; middle C, sine timbre
```

<!-- BUILD: wire create-periodic-wave to accept a list of harmonic amplitudes (one float per harmonic, index i = i-th harmonic) and return a voice handle. note/strike extended to accept an optional voice argument (default = piano). -->

The list `(list 1.0)` says \"first harmonic at amplitude 1.0, all others zero.\" The result is a sine wave — the same sound as `(tone 261.63 0.5)` (which is what middle C at quarter-note duration would be at 120 bpm).

Not interesting yet. Let's add more harmonics.

---


### A voice with two harmonics

Add the second harmonic at half the amplitude of the first. The second harmonic is an octave above the fundamental, so we're blending the pitch with its octave.

*[needs: GAP-4]*

```scheme
(define octave-voice
  (create-periodic-wave
    (list 1.0 0.5)))  ;; fundamental + octave at half strength

(note/strike 48 'half 0.7 octave-voice)  ;; C3, with its octave mixed in
```

You hear C3, but it sounds **fuller** — because the octave (C4) is quietly present. This is still simple, but it's no longer a pure sine. It has two partials.

---


### A sawtooth voice (all harmonics, decreasing)

A **sawtooth wave** has all harmonics present, each one's amplitude inversely proportional to its number: the second harmonic is half as loud as the first, the third is one-third, the fourth is one-quarter, and so on. It sounds **bright and buzzy** — lots of high-frequency content.

*[needs: GAP-4]*

```scheme
(define sawtooth-voice
  (create-periodic-wave
    (list 1.0
          (/ 1 2.0)
          (/ 1 3.0)
          (/ 1 4.0)
          (/ 1 5.0)
          (/ 1 6.0)
          (/ 1 7.0)
          (/ 1 8.0))))  ;; eight harmonics, amplitudes 1, 1/2, 1/3, ... 1/8

(note/strike 55 'quarter 0.6 sawtooth-voice)  ;; G3, sawtooth timbre
```

Now we hear a bright, edgy sound. The higher harmonics give it that buzz.

[VISUAL: Waveform of one period of the sawtooth — a rising ramp that drops sharply, repeating. Spectrum below showing the eight harmonics as bars at 1×, 2×, 3×, ... 8× the fundamental frequency, heights decreasing as 1, 1/2, 1/3, ... 1/8.]

---


### A square voice (odd harmonics only)

A **square wave** has only the odd harmonics (1st, 3rd, 5th, 7th, ...), each with amplitude inversely proportional to its number. It sounds **hollow and reedy** — less bright than a sawtooth because the even harmonics are missing.

*[needs: GAP-4]*

```scheme
(define square-voice
  (create-periodic-wave
    (list 1.0
          0.0          ;; no 2nd harmonic
          (/ 1 3.0)
          0.0          ;; no 4th
          (/ 1 5.0)
          0.0          ;; no 6th
          (/ 1 7.0)
          0.0)))       ;; no 8th

(note/strike 62 'quarter 0.7 square-voice)  ;; D4, square timbre
```

The odd-harmonic recipe gives you that clarinet-like hollow quality.

---


### A warm cello-section voice

A cello section has strong low harmonics and a gentle roll-off. Let's author one by hand.

*[needs: GAP-4]*

```scheme
(define cello-section
  (create-periodic-wave
    (list 1.0      ;; fundamental, full
          0.6      ;; 2nd harmonic, strong
          0.4      ;; 3rd, present
          0.25     ;; 4th, softer
          0.15     ;; 5th, fading
          0.08     ;; 6th, faint
          0.04     ;; 7th, very faint
          0.02)))  ;; 8th, almost gone

(note/strike 36 'whole 0.8 cello-section)  ;; C2, low and warm
```

This sounds **warm and full** — the strong first three harmonics give body, the gentle fade keeps it from being harsh. One synthesized note, but it feels like eight cellos playing together.

---


### A bright flute-section voice

A flute has a strong fundamental and very few upper harmonics — mostly just the first and a whisper of the second. Let's make a flute-section voice.

*[needs: GAP-4]*

```scheme
(define flute-section
  (create-periodic-wave
    (list 1.0      ;; fundamental, dominant
          0.15     ;; 2nd, faint
          0.05     ;; 3rd, barely there
          0.02     ;; 4th, almost silent
          0.0      ;; rest silent
          0.0
          0.0
          0.0)))

(note/strike 72 'half 0.6 flute-section)  ;; C5, light and airy
```

The result is **soft and pure** — almost sine-like, but with a hint of breath from the faint second harmonic.

---


### A clarinet-like voice (odd harmonics, shaped)

Clarinets emphasize odd harmonics, like a square wave, but with a more careful taper. Let's shape one.

*[needs: GAP-4]*

```scheme
(define clarinet-voice
  (create-periodic-wave
    (list 1.0      ;; 1st (fundamental)
          0.0      ;; 2nd (silent)
          0.5      ;; 3rd (strong)
          0.0      ;; 4th (silent)
          0.3      ;; 5th (moderate)
          0.0      ;; 6th (silent)
          0.15     ;; 7th (faint)
          0.0      ;; 8th (silent)
          0.08     ;; 9th (very faint)
          0.0)))   ;; 10th (silent)

(note/strike 58 'quarter 0.7 clarinet-voice)  ;; Bb3, reedy
```

The odd-harmonic emphasis gives it that **reedy, woody** character.

[VISUAL: Spectrum of the clarinet voice — bars at harmonics 1, 3, 5, 7, 9, with heights 1.0, 0.5, 0.3, 0.15, 0.08. Even harmonics (2, 4, 6, 8, 10) are absent (zero bars).]

---


### A brass-section voice (many strong harmonics)

Brass instruments — trumpets, trombones — have many strong harmonics, especially in the mid-range. Let's make a brass-section voice.

*[needs: GAP-4]*

```scheme
(define brass-section
  (create-periodic-wave
    (list 1.0      ;; 1st
          0.7      ;; 2nd, strong
          0.6      ;; 3rd, strong
          0.55     ;; 4th, still strong
          0.5      ;; 5th, strong
          0.4      ;; 6th, moderate
          0.3      ;; 7th, moderate
          0.2      ;; 8th, fading
          0.1      ;; 9th, faint
          0.05)))  ;; 10th, very faint

(note/strike 53 'half 0.85 brass-section)  ;; F3, bold and brassy
```

Many strong harmonics → **bright, bold, assertive**. One note sounds like a trumpet section.

---


### A string-quartet voice (balanced, rich)

A string quartet (two violins, viola, cello) playing in unison on one pitch would produce a balanced harmonic spectrum — strong low and mid harmonics, gentle taper. Let's author one.

*[needs: GAP-4]*

```scheme
(define string-quartet
  (create-periodic-wave
    (list 1.0      ;; fundamental, full
          0.65     ;; 2nd, strong
          0.55     ;; 3rd, strong
          0.4      ;; 4th, moderate
          0.3      ;; 5th, moderate
          0.2      ;; 6th, fading
          0.12     ;; 7th, faint
          0.07     ;; 8th, very faint
          0.04     ;; 9th, almost gone
          0.02)))  ;; 10th, trace

(note/strike 60 'whole 0.75 string-quartet)  ;; C4, warm and rich
```

This sounds **lush and full** — the kind of sound you'd get from four string players breathing together on one pitch.

---


### A glass-harmonica voice (gentle, eerie)

A glass harmonica (or glass harp) has a very pure tone with a slow, gentle build of harmonics. Let's make a voice inspired by that.

*[needs: GAP-4]*

```scheme
(define glass-voice
  (create-periodic-wave
    (list 1.0      ;; fundamental, pure
          0.08     ;; 2nd, faint
          0.05     ;; 3rd, very faint
          0.03     ;; 4th, trace
          0.02     ;; 5th, barely there
          0.01     ;; 6th, almost silent
          0.005    ;; 7th, silent
          0.002))) ;; 8th, silent

(note/strike 76 'whole 0.5 glass-voice)  ;; E5, ethereal and pure
```

The result is **ghostly and clear** — almost sine-like, but with a faint shimmer from the trace harmonics.

---


### A gamelan-like voice (inharmonic partials)

Most of what we've built so far uses **harmonic** partials — whole-number multiples of the fundamental. But some instruments (bells, gongs, gamelan metallophones) have **inharmonic** partials — frequencies that are NOT whole-number multiples. We can approximate that by carefully choosing harmonic amplitudes to emphasize non-adjacent partials, creating a **clangorous, metallic** timbre.

*[needs: GAP-4]*

```scheme
(define gamelan-voice
  (create-periodic-wave
    (list 1.0      ;; 1st (fundamental)
          0.1      ;; 2nd, very faint
          0.6      ;; 3rd, strong (creates a slight \"clang\")
          0.05     ;; 4th, faint
          0.4      ;; 5th, moderate (more clang)
          0.02     ;; 6th, trace
          0.3      ;; 7th, moderate (adds shimmer)
          0.01     ;; 8th, silent
          0.2      ;; 9th, faint (more shimmer)
          0.0)))   ;; 10th, silent

(note/strike 64 'half 0.7 gamelan-voice)  ;; E4, metallic and shimmering
```

The gaps between strong harmonics (1, 3, 5, 7, 9) create a **metallic, ringing** quality — not quite a true inharmonic instrument, but closer to the feel of a bronze gong than a cello.

[VISUAL: Spectrum showing the gamelan voice — tall bars at harmonics 1, 3, 5, 7, 9; very short bars at 2, 4, 6, 8; harmonic 10 absent. The uneven distribution gives the clangorous character.]

---


### A human-voice vowel (an \"ah\" sound)

Human vowels are shaped by **formants** — frequency regions where certain harmonics are amplified by the shape of the vocal tract. An \"ah\" vowel (as in \"father\") has formants around 700 Hz and 1200 Hz. If our fundamental is A3 (220 Hz), we want to boost the harmonics near those frequencies.

Harmonic 3 ≈ 660 Hz (close to 700 Hz).  
Harmonic 5 ≈ 1100 Hz (close to 1200 Hz).

Let's shape a voice that emphasizes those harmonics.

*[needs: GAP-4]*

```scheme
(define ah-vowel
  (create-periodic-wave
    (list 1.0      ;; 1st (220 Hz)
          0.3      ;; 2nd (440 Hz)
          0.8      ;; 3rd (660 Hz) — first formant region
          0.4      ;; 4th (880 Hz)
          0.9      ;; 5th (1100 Hz) — second formant region
          0.3      ;; 6th (1320 Hz)
          0.2      ;; 7th (1540 Hz)
          0.1)))   ;; 8th (1760 Hz)

(note/strike 57 'half 0.65 ah-vowel)  ;; A3, \"ah\" vowel timbre
```

The boost at harmonics 3 and 5 gives it a **vocal quality** — not a perfect sung \"ah,\" but recognizably voice-like.

---


### An \"ee\" vowel

An \"ee\" vowel (as in \"see\") has formants around 270 Hz and 2300 Hz. For A3 (220 Hz):

Harmonic 1 ≈ 220 Hz (close to 270 Hz).  
Harmonic 10 ≈ 2200 Hz (close to 2300 Hz).

We'll boost harmonic 1 (already full) and harmonic 10.

*[needs: GAP-4]*

```scheme
(define ee-vowel
  (create-periodic-wave
    (list 1.0      ;; 1st (220 Hz) — first formant region
          0.2      ;; 2nd
          0.15     ;; 3rd
          0.1      ;; 4th
          0.08     ;; 5th
          0.06     ;; 6th
          0.05     ;; 7th
          0.04     ;; 8th
          0.03     ;; 9th
          0.7)))   ;; 10th (2200 Hz) — second formant region

(note/strike 57 'half 0.6 ee-vowel)  ;; A3, \"ee\" vowel timbre
```

The strong high harmonic (10th) gives it that **bright, frontal \"ee\"** character.

---


### A choir voice (blend of \"ah\" and \"oo\")

A choir singing a blended vowel might have a spectrum between \"ah\" and \"oo.\" \"Oo\" (as in \"too\") has formants around 300 Hz and 800 Hz. Let's blend the two.

*[needs: GAP-4]*

```scheme
(define choir-voice
  (create-periodic-wave
    (list 1.0      ;; 1st (fundamental, covers \"oo\" 300 Hz region)
          0.5      ;; 2nd (440 Hz)
          0.7      ;; 3rd (660 Hz, \"ah\" formant)
          0.6      ;; 4th (880 Hz, \"oo\" formant region)
          0.6      ;; 5th (1100 Hz, \"ah\" formant)
          0.3      ;; 6th
          0.2      ;; 7th
          0.1      ;; 8th
          0.05     ;; 9th
          0.02)))  ;; 10th

(note/strike 60 'whole 0.7 choir-voice)  ;; C4, warm choral blend
```

The balanced mid-range harmonics give it a **warm, vocal, choral** quality.

